TI  - Research on the characteristics and influencing factors of arc in segmented insulators
PY  - 2025
JO  - Physica Scripta
DO  - 10.1088/1402-4896/add186
AB  - The segmented insulator is an indispensable electrical insulation component in the pantograph-catenary system but is highly susceptible to damage from persistent arcs during pantograph transitions, causing critical issues like severe arc horn erosion, insulating rod failure, and short circuits. Due to complex operating conditions, the factors influencing arcs and underlying mechanisms remain unclear. In this article, a novel multiphysics simulation model is developed to conduct a quantitative analysis of arc characteristics. Firstly, a magnetohydrodynamic (MHD) model in COMSOL investigates arc evolution patterns and elucidates the influence principle of the Kármán vortex street on arc behavior. Then, key factors affecting voltage and temperature are systematically analyzed, revealing that under low wind speeds and high currents, short-circuit risks increase and arc horn erosion intensifies, under strong wind speeds and high currents, insulating rod erosion becomes more pronounced. Finally, a segmented insulator experimental platform was constructed, with a maximum voltage deviation of 1.84% between experimental and simulated results, validating the simulation’s accuracy. This work indicates the mechanism of arc evolution in segmented insulators, explains the effects of wind speed and current on the arc, and provides a crucial theoretical foundation for mitigating arc erosion and reducing short-circuit risks. © 2025 IOP Publishing Ltd. All rights, including for text and data mining, AI training, and similar technologies, are reserved.
